We quantify the uncertainty in economic damages arising from uncertainty in the temperature optimum (e.g., 
   Figs. 2 and 
   4 and 
   
    SI Appendix, Table S1
   ), as well as the uncertainty arising from lagged responses to temperature fluctuations (
   
    SI Appendix, Table S2
   ). We also explore additional aspects of the relationship between temperature and GDP growth. For example, we find that historical temperature fluctuations explain on average 8.6% of the overall variation in country-level annual income growth fluctuations during our study period (
   
    SI Appendix, Fig. S2
   ). Likewise, given the shape of the temperature–growth response function (
   Fig. 1
    B
   ), temperature fluctuations around a stable mean will induce a negative trend in per capita GDP. However, we find that the magnitude of this effect is small compared with the impact of long-term warming (
   
    SI Appendix, Fig. S3
   ).
